<font class="body">
<table width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
<tr align=left>
	<td colspan=2><font class="pressReleaseTitle">
		<b>CEA Honors Hall of Fame Inductees at 2000 International CES</b></font></td></tr>
<tr align=left>
	<td colspan=2><font class="pressReleaseSubTitle">
		<b>CEA Inaugurates Top 50 Innovators to the CE Hall of Fame</b></font><hr noshade size=1></td></tr>
<!--
<tr><td bgcolor="000000" colspan=2><hr noshade size=2></td></tr>
-->
<tr><td align=left><font class="pressReleaseLocation">
		<b>,</b></font></td>
	<td align=right><font class="pressReleaseDate">
		1/6/00</font></td></tr>
<tr><td colspan=2><hr noshade size=2></td></tr>
<!--
<tr><td bgcolor="000000" colspan=2><hr noshade size=1></td></tr>
-->
</table>

<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0 width=80%>
<tr><td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
	<td><font class="pressReleaseBody"><title>CEA Honors Hall of Fame Inductees at 2000 International CES</title>To recognize the contributions of the 

true pioneers of the consumer electronics industry, the Consumer Electronics 

Association (CEA) announced the first 50 inductees into its Consumer 

Electronics Hall of Fame today.

<p>

Photographs and short profiles of each inductee are on display at several 

locations in the Las Vegas Convention Center and Sands Exposition and 

Convention Center during the 2000 International CES held here January 6-9.  

Videotape segments displaying the inductees will be shown at today’s opening 

keynote address.

<p>

“This is one of the rare occasions that the industry gets to commemorate the 

technological advancements it has provided and the far-reaching impact these 

achievements have had in the lives of consumers worldwide.  It presents us 

with the opportunity to reflect back on the accomplishments of our industry 

and pay tribute to those individuals who have paved the way for today’s 

workstyle and lifestyle products,” said Gary Shapiro, CEA president.  

“Individually, and in some cases, together they made significant 

contributions to the development of all consumer electronics products.  

Without their creations, the world would be a very different place.”

<p>

A panel comprised of 11 media and industry professionals judged nominations 

for the Consumer Electronics Hall of Fame.  Sitting on the panel were: Jim 

Barry, media spokesperson for CEA; Brian Fenton, executive editor, Stereo 

Review’s Sound & Vision magazine; Howard Geltzer, chairman and co-founder of 

Geltzer & Company Inc.; Robert Gerson, editor-in-chief of TWICE magazine; 

Pam Golden Loder, partner at Golden Loder Associates; Frank McCann, 

president, McCann Public Relations; Janet Pinkerton, editor-in-chief, 

Dealerscope Consumer Electronics Marketplace magazine; Martin Porter, 

founder and publisher, AutoMedia and CarSound magazines and publishing 

director of Miller Freeman PSN; Richard Sherwin, vice president corporate 

communications for Roxy.com; John Taylor, vice president Public Affairs and 

Communications for Zenith Electronics Corp. and Stewart Wolpin, co-founder 

and editor-at-large of etown.com: The Consumer Electronics Source.

In addition to the pictorial display and video, CEA published a book that 

chronicles the accomplishments of each inductee.  The books will be 

distributed at the 2000 International CES.  A complete list of inductees and 

their profiles can be viewed online at www.CESweb.org and www.CE.org.

The 2000 CE Hall of Fame inductees are as follows:

<ul>

<li> Benjamin Abrams, founder of Emerson Radio and Phonograph Corp.

<li> Robert Adler, inventor of the remote control

<li> Edwin Armstrong, creator of FM radio

<li> John Logie Baird, developer of television

<li> William Balderston, former president, Philco Corp. and leader in 

developing car radio

<li> John Bardeen, co-inventor of the transistor

<li> Alexander Graham Bell, inventor of the telephone

<li> Andre Blay, creator of home video sales

<li> Walter Brattain, co-inventor of the transistor

<li> Karl Ferdinand Braun, inventor of the oscillograph

<li> Nolan Bushnell,  entrepreneur who kicked off video game craze

<li> Powell Crosley, Jr., first mass-market radio

<li> Lee DeForest, vacuum tube development

<li> Ray Dolby, founder and chairman of Dolby Laboratories Inc.

<li> Allen Dumont, founder of the Dumont Television Network and the 

first CRTs

<li> Thomas Edison, invented the light bulb, storage battery and 

phonograph

<li> Carl Eilers, developer of stereo FM and stereo TV

<li> Philo T. Farnsworth, developed TV based on cathode ray tube

<li> Reginald Fessenden, developer of radio broadcasting

<li> Avery Fisher, invented the transistorized amplifier, combination 

stereo radio/phonograph

<li> Frank Freimann, president of Magnavox, known for merchandising

<li> Paul Galvin, founded Motorola, mass produced car radio

<li> Charles Ginsberg, leader in developing video recording

<li> Peter Goldmark, invented the 33 RPM vinyl LP record and the first 

color TV system

<li> Dr. Sidney Harman, developed the first receiver

<li> Heinrich Hertz, first to demonstrate the production and detection 

of Maxwell’s waves

<li> Masaru Ibuka, co-founder of Sony

<li> Eldridge Johnson, founder and president of The Victor Talking 

Machine Co.

<li> Jack Kilby, co-inventor of the integrated circuit

<li> Henry Kloss, acoustic suspension speaker and the large screen 

projection TV

<li> John Koss, Sr., designed first commercial headphones

<li> David Lachenbruch, dean of consumer electronics journalists

<li> James B. Lansing, speaker technology

<li> Saul Marantz, pioneer in high-fidelity music systems

<li> Guglielmo Marconi, inventor of wireless telegraphy

<li> Konosuke Matsushita, founder of Matsushita Electric Industrial Co.

<li> Commander Eugene F. McDonald, founder of Zenith Radio Corp.

<li> Akio Morita, co-founder of Sony

<li> Robert Noyce, co-inventor of the microchip, the integrated circuit, 

co-founder Fairchild Semi-Counductor, Co., founder of Intel Corp.

<li> Vlademar Poulsen, inventor of telegraphone, wire recording device

<li> Ed Roberts, designed and built the first successful personal 

computer, The Altair 8800

<li> David Sarnoff, radio and television pioneer

<li> Hermon Scott, founder of H.H. Scott Co.

<li> Yuma Shiraishi, co-founder of the VHS format

<li> William Shockley, solid state physicist

<li> Ross Siragusa, Sr., founder of the Admiral Corp.

<li> Shizuo Takano, lead the development of the VHS format

<li> Nikola Tesla, pioneer in electric power, invented the 

electro-magnetic motor

<li> Jack Wayman, EIA and CEA leader

<li> Vladmir Zworykin, instrumental in the invention of TV

</ul>



CEA is a sector of the Electronic Industries Alliance (EIA), the 76-year-old 

Arlington, Virginia-based trade organization representing all facets of 

electronics manufacturing.  CEA represents more than 500 U.S. manufacturers 

of audio, video, accessories, mobile electronics, communication, information 

technology and multimedia products that are sold through consumer channels.

<p>

CEA also sponsors and manages the International CES – Your Source for 

Workstyle and Lifestyle TechnologySM.  All profits from CES are reinvested 

into industry services, including technical training and education, product 

promotion, engineering standards development, market research and 

governmental and legal affairs support.  As the first major technology event 

of the new millennium, the 2000 International CES is the launch pad for 21st 

century technology.

</font></td></tr>



</table>
